<div id="Idea_4155"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4155-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4155">Tort Reform&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/9774-4049">kdtroxel</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">22 hours ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">20.	Tort Reform: Maximum cap on lawsuit damages/payouts, of $250,000.  I am not a lawyer, but I do know that a nationalized health insurance program cannot operate without tort reform.  Meaning should you sue for multiple damage items, the maximum payout for all items would be $250,000; each count would not be $250,000 each but $250,000 total.  Damages are items beyond recovery of basis. <br/>•	<br/>Without tort reform and with medical profits being capped, then lawsuits would jeopardize the ability for all health institutions to operate.  Without tort reform and with medical profits capped, then a rash of hospital and clinic closings would ensue; if a national health care system were in place.<br/></div>
